1. e4 { The most popular White's first move. We don't want to go into a discussion if it's the best though. }  c5 { And this is the Sicilian Defence. The most popular, the sharpest and best-scoring response to 1. e4 Black has 49.4% according to MegaDatabase 2023. Black fights for the centre and unlike to 1...e5 he breaks the symmetry immediately. } 
2. Nf3 { By far the main move. White develops the knight to its natural square and is one step closer to castling. He is planning to push d4 leading to the Open Sicilian, which is considered to be the most challenging. Indeed, Black is put to test, at the same time White also needs to know a lot. Exchanging c-pawn for the d-pawn is in Black's favour from a pure positional point of view, and White must prove that he can keep the initiative going. } ( { 2.Nc3 } { , } { 2.c3 } { and many other 2nd move alternatives like } { 2.b4 } { or even } 2.Na3 { are obviously covered in the LTR courses. This one is no exception. These are certainly interesting and often tricky lines, but they altogether can't be even compared to the Open Sicilian. } )  a6 { This is our choice O'Kelly, we will get back to this topic later. At this stage we would like to mention that the Sicilian Defence is a very rich opening and White must be ready for a bunch of different setups. Let's have a short look at some of them. } ( { ◼️ } 2...Nc6 { The most natural move. } 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6  There is also 4{...g6 Accelerated Dragon, 4...e6 Taimanov or 4...e5 Kalashnikov. } 5.Nc3 e5 { Again there are some options like 5...e6 Four Knights or 5...d6 Classical. } 6.Ndb5 d6 { This is the Sveshnikov Variation, which is one of the best lines. } ) ( { ◼️ } 2...d6  The most popular choice, Black makes sure White doesn't have {e4-e5 once he develops the king's knight. } 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 { Here 5...d6 is another move order for the Classical Variation and 5...g6 is the Dragon. } 5...a6 { And this is the Najdorf Variation, another top line. Btw, note that the ...a6 move is very often a useful move in the Sicilian. } ) ( { ◼️ } 2...e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4  Now 4{...Nf6 might lead to the Four Knights, 4...Nc6 is another move order for the Taimanov } 4...a6 { This is the Kan Variation, which is the most similar variation of the Sicilian Defence to the O'Kelly. You can read more about it here. } ) ( { ◼️ Let's mention also } 2...g6 { leading to the Accelerated Dragon or as some people classify this move order as Hyper-Accelerated. There is a course on Chessable called 'Accelerate the Dragon' - highly recommended! 😊 } ) 
