1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 ( 2.Nc3 a6 { 3.g3 } { enters the Closed Sicilian  and } 3.f4  is the Grand Prix Attack. Other 2nd move alternatives with some {g3 or f4 tries are covered here and Wing, Alapin & others can be found here. } )  a6 { We are at the starting point of the O'Kelly Variation of the Sicilian Defence. The variation is named after the famous Belgian player Alberic O'Kelly de Galway, grandmaster, correspondence grandmaster, World Correspondence Chess Champion of 1962, theoretician and arbiter. By playing the seemingly non-developing move ...a6, Black takes the very important b5-square under control and retains flexibility.This repertoire should suit players who are inclined to play a double-edged Sicilian with chances of taking over the initiative, and at the same time don't want to occupy themselves with learning and remembering the overwhelming amount of theory needed in the main Sicilians.A downside of playing the O'Kelly Sicilian is that White can get a slight opening advantage if he plays very accurately. However, there is a big upside. Black practically eliminates the risk of getting out prepared and running into an unplayable or simply lost position out of the opening, which is a real danger in the heavily-researched main Sicilian Variations. } 
3. -- { Let's see what are White's possibilities here. } ( { ◼️ } 3.d4 { The most popular and arguably the best move against all Sicilians except... the O'Kelly! It is played in more than 50% of the games in the lichess database. At an amateur level you should get this position every second game when playing the O'Kelly, so studying the first theoretical chapter should cover 50% of your repertoire. } 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5  The point. White's knight doesn't have the {b5 square available and has to retreat passively. Black immediately achieves equality and chances to take over the initiative. } ) ( { ◼️ } 3.c3  A very logical choice. The Alapin Variation of the Sicilian Defence {2. c3 is solid, but somewhat dull, and it's hard to get the advantage. With the inclusion of Nf3 and ...a6, one can argue it's a great version for the first player. Indeed, it is an improved version, but we will prove that things are far from simple. } 3...e6 4.d4 d5 { Here White has a choice. He can either take on d5 where he probably is not getting anything see the relevant chapter here or push } 5.e5 { This in turn is the Advance Variation of the French Defence where Black played ...a6 which is not considered the best. At the same time we are going to show that the move is useful and although White can get a small advantage, playing behind barricades might be easier for us. See here. } ) ( { ◼️ } 3.c4 { The most aggressive option. White attempts to get a Maroczy Bind structure characterised by pawns on e4 and c4 restricting the enemy. However, here may come the biggest surprise. } 3...Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5! { You can be certain that many experienced players don't know about this line. Now White has to be ready for a theoretical battle and opt for } 6.Nf5! { to fight for the advantage. Otherwise, Black is totally fine. } 6...d5 7.cxd5 Bxf5 8.exf5 Nd4 { For the moment White has two bishops and an extra pawn, but we have a lot of active play. As we will see in the theoretical chapter, with the best play White can get a symbolic advantage, but it is doubtful that Black has significant problems. } ) ( { ◼️ } 3.Nc3 { A normal developing move which most likely leads to the Kan Variation of the Sicilian Defence. } 3...b5 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e6 { What is important, this is not the most challenging line in the Kan, as explained in the informational line. } 6.Bd3 { The main move is covered here. } ( { 6.Be2 } { and } { 6.g3 } { are covered here and there is another chapter with } { 6.a3 } { , } 6.Be3 { and rare tries on move 4. } ) ) ( { ◼️ Finally, we have a chapter covering 3rd move alternatives like } 3.g3 { Unfortunately, there is one Novelty where objectively White can get some advantage. At the same time, Black is still quite solid and shouldn't be worried. } ) 
