1. e4 e6
2. d4 d5 { This is the French Defence. What does it have to do with our repertoire? Well, we need to learn something which overlaps with this opening. } 
3. e5 ( { The Advanced Variation which is the 3rd most popular choice. Much more often played and maybe more challenging are } { 3.Nc3 } { and } 3.Nd2 { . } )  c5 { Black attacks the centre. } 
4. c3 a6!? ( { And suddenly after } 5.Nf3  { we transpose to our repertoire  1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 e6 4.d4 d5 5.e5  Many might ask - is really 4...a6 a great move here? Objectively, it has to be admitted, this is not the best move. However, the move can be useful and taking into account the closed nature of the position it's not ridiculous. Actually there exist some normal lines where Black plays ...a6 later on, and we may transpose to such lines   for example see the model game Xie-Karpov   . From a practical perspective, our opponent has been lured into playing behind barricades and if he is not familiar with the Advanced Variation of the French he can be easily outplayed.  } ) ( { More common is } 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 Qb6  with {...Nh6-f5 next pressuring d4 quickly, or } 5...Bd7 { with ...Nge7-f5. } ) ( { Also } 4...Qb6 5.Nf3 Bd7!?  with {...Bb5 is an option. } ) 
