1. e4 c5 { “Less is more” Ludwig Mies van der Rohe  Nowadays, it's quite easy to generate hundreds of lines for an opening book, thanks to engines and databases. However, the crucial task lies in distinguishing what is truly relevant from what is not. While this can be a matter of debate, our courses aim to distill the essence of the opening. We strive to minimize the number of trainable lines, particularly with the O'Kelly, as having more lines than some Najdorf courses from the Lifetime Repertoire series would mean something went horribly wrong.But it’s not just about the number of lines. We also try to cut the number of moves to be memorized. At the same time, we provide ample explanations in the form of clickable variations when necessary. In some instances, we extend the main line with a sample continuation.We encourage you to focus on what is really important. If you want to be a better player, you must be always ready to find a good antidote on your own to some less critical moves, while having in mind ideas from the main lines of the opening. That said, we do understand some you may also want to train some of the lines in more depth, perhaps especially on a second pass through the course. So, in some cases, we have provided two versions of a trainable; a shorter default version, and an extended 'in detail' version, and you can take you pick of which suits you best. } 
