3. c3 { The second most popular reaction to the O'Kelly Variation and the best one apart from 3.c4. White wants to play an improved version of the Alapin Sicilian, where Black has spent a tempo on ...a6. White is able to get a slight advantage if he plays very accurately, but Black always keeps his share of chances. }  e6!? { I recommend playing in the spirit of the French Defence. The compromised position of the c-pawn seriously limits White's possibilities. } 
4. d4 d5
5. e5 { The critical move. White argues that he has a better version of the Advance Variation of the French Defence. }  Bd7 { We hint at the possibility of ...cxd4 followed by ...Bb5, but our preferred method of play will be ...Nc6 } 
6. Be2 { The one square development of the bishop may look modest, but thanks to it White faces less problems with protection of the d4-pawn and Black has to search for other sources of counterplay. }  Nc6
7. O-O Rc8 ( { Black could play } 7...cxd4 8.cxd4 Nge7 { , but then } 9.Nbd2  followed by {Nb3 is a bit problematic. }  { The advantage of  7...Rc8  is that  8.Nbd2  can be met by active play with ...Nb4.  } ) 
8. Na3! { Putting the knight on c2, where it covers the d4 and b4 points is the critical test of the variation and has been played by many strong players, most famous of them being Alexei Shirov. }  cxd4
9. cxd4 Qb6 ( 9...Bxa3 { can lead to a tenable, but cheerless position due to the white bishop pair and soft dark squares in Black's camp. Instead, we should start queenside counterplay. } ) 
10. Nc2 Na7! ( { An important maneuver with the idea of the light-squared bishops' exchange. The seemingly natural } 10...Nge7?! { runs into } 11.b4! { with a dangerous queenside grip in the making. } ) 
11. Ne3 Ne7⩲ { [%cal Bd7b5] [%cal Ge7c6] [%cal Ga7b5] } { In addition to ...Bb5, we get the ...Nc6 and ...Nb5 idea, with big pressure against d4. We are really solid here. We need to stay true to the engine evaluation of slightly better for White, but at the same time the position doesn't seem to give reasons to worry in practical play. } 
