22. Re1 Re8
23. Rfe3 Kf7 { This is visibly a much less effective way of organizing the forces than the above mentioned line with the rook on c6, which not only defends, but also attacks. Now, in comparison, Black is passive. But an important feature of positions like this is that White simply doesn't have much scope to improve his position further, because he has no constructive pawn breaks and the pressure on e6 alone is not enough to build an advantage. White decided to repeat the position and Black had no good way to stop it, so the game ended in a draw. } 
