{ This was the toughest tournament in my life. I had to face 9 strong players with average rating of 2563. I had a decent score 3/8 and this was the last round where I had to face a young grandmaster, a member of the Polish national team. }
1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 a6 { I have already lost 3 games in my beloved Accelerated Dragon in this tournament. Not necessarily because of the opening, but it's not always a good idea to let 2500+ opponents to be sure what I play and prepare only against it. I came to the conclusion the O'Kelly might be a good surprise. } 
3. Be2!? { And indeed, the O'Kelly was a surprise. However, my opponent came up with an interesting idea which was not included in our files before that game. Although the bishop is not most actively placed White is ready to castle and d2-d4 is still on the cards. Playing without Nc3 makes ...b5 less good which I knew, but... }  b5?! { I didn't react properly as I felt I could get away with this. The game is still interesting though and we can learn more about relevant Sicilian structures and we should especially try to understand how different the game is when White doesn't have the knight on c3. } ( 3...Nc6 { is our recommendation. } ) { See here. } 
4. d4 ( 4.a4 Bb7 { looked good to me, but... } 5.axb5 axb5 6.Rxa8 Bxa8 7.Nc3 b4 8.Nb5 Bxe4 9.d4⩲ { White has a huge initiative for the pawn. The game continuation was also nice for White. } )  cxd4
5. Nxd4 Bb7 { Everything would be fine if White developed the knight to c3 so then our b-pawn might go with tempo. } 
6. O-O { Teclaf shows a good understanding of the position. He just develops and doesn't care about the central pawn. Taking it would be suicidal. } ( 6.Nc3?! { would transpose to our repertoire where we believe Black is O.K. } 6...e6 7.O-O b4 8.Na4 Bxe4 { etc. } ) ( 6.c4⩲ { is the engine's choice. I am not sure if human would play this, but it is a good example of another way to make use of not having the knight on c3. } )  e5?! { The machine doesn't approve it, but what to do? } ( 6...e6 7.c4 { or } ( 7.a4 b4 8.Nd2 { is just better for White. Compared to normal lines White's queen's knight is much better placed. } ) ) 
7. Nb3?! ( 7.Nf3! { was even stronger. } 7...Qc7 8.Nc3 Nf6 9.Nd5 Nxd5 10.exd5  Our structure is problematic because of lack of proper development. White is much faster to strike on the queenside before we could launch our f-pawn or attack {d5. } 10...Bc5 11.c3 O-O 12.a4± )  Nf6 ( 7...Bxe4 { is risky, but including ...Nf6 and Bg5 was worse. } 8.Nc3 Bc6 9.a4⩲ ) 
8. Bg5 Bxe4!? { It's a practical decision to suffer at least for a pawn. It's not objectively fully correct though. } ( 8...Be7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.Nc3 { it's not the end of the world, but Black is strategically outplayed due to a weakness of the d5 square. } ) 
9. Nc3?! ( 9.f4± { was a powerful move to blast open the position when Black's king is still in the middle. } )  Bc6! { The bishop on b7 would be too vulnerable. Here it blocks the queen's knight, however this is less important. The priority is to keep the game as closed as possible before castling. } ( 9...Bb7? 10.Bf3 Nc6 ( 10...Bxf3? 11.Qxf3 Nc6 12.Ne4+- ) 11.Nd5 Be7 12.Bxf6 Bxf6 13.Nc5± ) 
10. Bf3?! ( 10.f4! e4 11.Nd5 { still gave White some edge. } )  Be7 { All of a sudden White's initiative is only sufficient to compensate a missing pawn. } 
11. Re1 d6 { More precise was } ( 11...Bxf3 12.Qxf3 Nc6= { Black just castles next. } ) 
12. Bxf6 Bxf6
13. Nd4 { A nice resource. The knight was not doing much on b3. }  Bxf3
14. Qxf3 Ra7
